4e696fc9-4ff9-4ca9-b80c-a729909136b8.052fe025-bf80-4a65-9547-88c71843c9c4.prompt=Please choose your version of uCMDB\: 4e696fc9-4ff9-4ca9-b80c-a729909136b8.12c14bac-6555-4d74-9f5b-97010ab335ad.prompt=scheme\://domain\:port/path?query_string\#fragment_id 4e696fc9-4ff9-4ca9-b80c-a729909136b8.18492fa6-ad8e-4944-8c74-6afdbc39eda8.description=
This is a soft copy of 'Http Client' customized for the GET method (the input 'method'\='GET' should not be changed). Check the linked 'Http Client' operation.

Inputs
    url - The web address to make the request to. This must be a standard URL as specified in RFC 3986. This is a required input.
Format\: scheme\://domain\:port/path?query_string\#fragment_id
Examples\: https\://[fe80\:\:1260\:4bff\:fe49\:42fc]\:8080/my/path?key1\=val1&key2\=val2\#my_fragment
    authType - The type of authentication used by this operation when trying to execute the request on the target server. The authentication is not preemptive\: a plain request not including authentication info will be made and only when the server responds with a 'WWW-Authenticate' header the client will send required headers. If the server needs no authentication but you specify one in this input the request will work nevertheless. The client cannot choose the authentication method and there is no fallback so you have to know which one you need. If the web application and proxy use different authentication types, these must be specified like in the Example model. 
Default value\: basic
Valid values\: basic, digest, ntlm, kerberos, any, anonymous, "" or a list of valid values separated by comma.
Example\: basic,digest
    username - The user name used for authentication. For NTLM authentication, the required format is 'domain\user' and if you only specify the 'user' it will append a dot like '.\user' so that a local user on the target machine can be used. In order for all authentication schemes to work (except Kerberos) username is required.
    password - The password used for authentication.
    preemptiveAuth - If this field is 'true' authentication info will be sent in the first request. If this is 'false' a request with no authentication info will be made and if server responds with 401 and a header like WWW-Authenticate\: Basic realm\="myRealm" only then the authentication info will be sent.
Default value\: true
Valid values\: true, false
    proxyHost - The proxy server used to access the web site.
    proxyPort - The proxy server port. Default value\: 8080. Valid values\: -1, and positive integer values. When the value is '-1' the default port of the scheme, specified in the 'proxyHost', will be used.
    proxyUsername - The user name used when connecting to the proxy. The 'authType' input will be used to choose authentication type. The 'Basic' and 'Digest' proxy auth type are supported.
    proxyPassword - The proxy server password associated with the proxyUsername input value.
    trustAllRoots - Specifies whether to enable weak security over SSL/TSL. A certificate is trusted even if no trusted certification authority issued it.
Default value\: false
Valid values\: true, false
    x509HostnameVerifier - Specifies the way the server hostname must match a domain name in the subject's Common Name (CN) or subjectAltName field of the X.509 certificate. The hostname verification system prevents communication with other hosts other than the ones you intended. This is done by checking that the hostname is in the subject alternative name extension of the certificate. This system is designed to ensure that, if an attacker(Man In The Middle) redirects traffic to his machine, the client will not accept the connection. If you set this input to "allow_all", this verification is ignored and you become vulnerable to security attacks. For the value "browser_compatible" the hostname verifier works the same way as Curl and Firefox. The hostname must match either the first CN, or any of the subject-alts. A wildcard can occur in the CN, and in any of the subject-alts. The only difference between "browser_compatible" and "strict" is that a wildcard (such as "*.foo.com") with "browser_compatible" matches all subdomains, including "a.b.foo.com". From the security perspective, to provide protection against possible Man-In-The-Middle attacks, we strongly recommend to use "strict" option.
Default value\: strict
Valid values\: strict, browser_compatible, allow_all
    trustKeystore - The pathname of the Java TrustStore file. This contains certificates from other parties that you expect to communicate with, or from Certificate Authorities that you trust to identify other parties.  If the protocol (specified by the 'url') is not 'https' or if trustAllRoots is 'true' this input is ignored.
Default value\: /java/lib/security/cacerts
Format\: Java KeyStore (JKS)
    trustPassword - The password associated with the TrustStore file. If trustAllRoots is false and trustKeystore is empty, trustPassword default will be supplied.
Default value\: changeit
    keystore - The pathname of the Java KeyStore file. You only need this if the server requires client authentication. If the protocol (specified by the 'url') is not 'https' or if trustAllRoots is 'true' this input is ignored.
Default value\: /java/lib/security/cacerts
Format\: Java KeyStore (JKS)
    keystorePassword - The password associated with the KeyStore file. If trustAllRoots is false and keystore is empty, keystorePassword default will be supplied.
Default value\: changeit
    connectTimeout - The time to wait for a connection to be established, in seconds. A timeout value of '0' represents an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0
Format\: an integer representing seconds
Examples\: 10, 20
    socketTimeout - The timeout for waiting for data (a maximum period inactivity between two consecutive data packets), in seconds. A socketTimeout value of '0' represents an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0
Format\: an integer representing seconds
    useCookies - Specifies whether to enable cookie tracking or not. Cookies are stored between consecutive calls in a serializable session object therefore they will be available on a branch level (same subflow, same lane). If you specify a non-boolean value, the default value is used.
Default value\: true
Valid values\: true,false
    keepAlive - Specifies whether to create a shared connection that will be used in subsequent calls. If keepAlive is false, the already open connection will be used and after execution it will close it. The operation will use a connection pool stored in a GlobalSessionObject that will be available throughout the execution (the flow and subflows, between parallel split lanes).
Default value\: true
Valid values\: true, false
    connectionsMaxPerRoute - The maximum limit of connections on a per route basis. The default will create no more than 2 concurrent connections per given route.
Default value\: 2
    connectionsMaxTotal - The maximum limit of connections in total. The default will create no more than 20 concurrent connections in total.
Default value\: 20
    followRedirects - Specifies whether the HTTP client automatically follows redirects.  Redirects explicitly prohibited by the HTTP specification as requiring user intervention will not be followed (redirects on POST and PUT requests that are converted to GET requests). If you specify a non-boolean value, the default value is used.
Default value\: true
Valid values\: true, false
    headers - The list containing the headers to use for the request separated by new line (CRLF).The header name - value pair will be separated by "\:".
Format\: Conforming with HTTP standard for headers (RFC 2616).
Examples\: Accept\:text/plain
    destinationFile - The absolute path of a file on disk where to save the entity returned by the response. 'returnResult' will no longer be populated with the entity if this is specified. You should not use this for method\=HEAD or OPTIONS.	Example\: C\:\temp\destinationFile.txt
    responseCharacterSet - The character encoding to be used for the HTTP response. If responseCharacterSet is empty, the charset from the 'Content-Type' HTTP response header will be used. If responseCharacterSet is empty and the charset from the HTTP response Content-Type header is empty, the default value will be used. You should not use this for method\=HEAD or OPTIONS.
Default value\: ISO-8859-1
    queryParams - The list containing query parameters to append to the URL. The names and the values must not be URL encoded unless you specify "queryParamsAreURLEncoded"\=true because if they are encoded and "queryParamsAreURLEncoded"\=false they will get double encoded. The separator between name-value pairs is  "&". The query name will be separated from query value by "\=". Note that you need to URL encode at least "&" to "%26" and "\=" to "%3D" and set "queryParamsAreURLEncoded"\="true" if you leave the other special URL characters unencoded they will be encoded by the HTTP Client.
Examples\: parameterName1\=parameterValue1¶meterName2\=parameterValue2;
    queryParamsAreURLEncoded - Specifies whether to encode  (according to the url encoding standard) the queryParams. If you set "queryParamsAreURLEncoded"\=true and you have invalid characters in 'queryParams' they will get encoded anyway. If you specify a non-boolean value, the default value is used.
Default value\: false
Valid values\: true, false
    queryParamsAreFormEncoded - Specifies whether to encode the queryParams in the the default format used by the apache http client library - form format. If this input is true then all characters will be encoded based on the queryParamsAreURLEncoded input.If queryParamsAreFormEncoded\=false all reserved chars are not encoded no matter of queryParamsAreURLEncoded input.The only exceptions are for space(' ')character which is encoded as %20 and + (plus) which is encoded as %20 and not encoded if queryParamsAreURLEncoded\=false. Check the "v2.0" folder description for more details.
Default value\: true. 
Valid values\: true, false
Example\: query\=test te%20@st will be encoded in query\=test%20te%20@st
    method - The HTTP method used. This is a required input.

Outputs
    returnResult - This will contain the response entity (unless 'destinationFile' is specified). In case of an error this output will contain the error message.
    exception - In case of success response, this result is empty. In case of failure response, this result contains the java stack trace of the runtime exception.
    statusCode - The HTTP status code.
Format\: 1xx (Informational - Request received, continuing process), 2xx (Success - The action was successfully received, understood, and accepted), 3xx (Redirection - Further action must be taken in order to complete the request), 4xx (Client Error - The request contains bad syntax or cannot be fulfilled), 5xx Server Error - The server failed to fulfil an apparently valid request)
Examples\: 200, 404
    finalLocation - The final location after redirects.
Format\: URL
    responseHeaders - The list containing the headers of the response message, separated by newline.
Format\: This is conforming with HTTP standard for headers (RFC 2616).
    protocolVersion - The HTTP protocol version.
Examples\: HTTP/1.1
    reasonPhrase - The reason phrase from the origin HTTP response. This depends on the status code and are according to RFC 1945 and RFC 2048
Examples\: (HTTP 1.0)\: OK, Created, Accepted, No Content, Moved Permanently, Moved Temporarily, Not Modified, Bad Request, Unauthorized, Forbidden, Not Found, Internal Server Error, Not Implemented, Bad Gateway, Service Unavailable	Values (HTTP 1.1)\: Continue, Temporary Redirect, Method Not Allowed, Conflict, Precondition Failed, Request Too Long, Request-URI Too Long, Unsupported Media Type, Multiple Choices, See Other, Use Proxy, Payment Required, Not Acceptable, Proxy Authentication Required, Request Timeout, Switching Protocols, Non Authoritative Information, Reset Content, Partial Content, Gateway Timeout, Http Version Not Supported, Gone, Length Required, Requested Range Not Satisfiable, Expectation Failed
    returnCode - The returnCode of the operation\: 0 for success, -1 for failure.

Responses
    success - The operation completed without a runtime exception. So it will go to success for any  http codes even those in the 400-599 range.
    failure - A runtime exception occurred. This may be due to incorrectly formated inputs (authType, contentType, headers, method, proxy, queryParams, requestCharacterSet, responseCharacterSet, truststore, url), or failed ntlm or Kerberos authentication.

Notes
Check the "v2.0" folder description for more help.
4e696fc9-4ff9-4ca9-b80c-a729909136b8.214d8c66-52e4-4502-9dbc-5577e3bc7b87.description=
The flow will look up the IP for hostname from DNS server. If found the IP, it will check  if the CI with that IP exists in UCMDB. If IP exists, it will check if the CI with hostname exists in UCMDB. If hostname exists, then it will check  if host type CI is related to the ip CI.

Inputs\:
hostname - Fully qualified domain name. For example, myserver.rose.hp.com.
dnsServer - Optional input. Specify DNS server name or ip to look up the IP for the input hostname.
    cmdbHost - The host running UCMDB.
    cmdbPort - The UCMDB server port.
Default value\: 8080 
    protocol - The protocol used to connect to the UCMDB server. HTTPS (TLS) is supported only by UCMDB version 9.x and 10.x.
    Valid values\: http, https
    Default value\: http
    username - The user name used for the UCMDB server connection.
Default value\: admin 
    password - The password associated with the  input value.
    cmdbVersion - The major version number of the UCMDB server.
Default value\: 7
Examples\: 7 (for UCMDB 7.0), 8 (for UCMDB 8.0)
    cmdbHostTypeList - The UCMDB CI types that belong to host CI types. Start with  the host type  that is more specific. For example, nt,unix.  If not specified,the following list will be used \: nt,unix,vmware_esx_server,cluster_resource_group,clusteredservice,terminalserver,vax,mainframe,lpar,host_node,node,host. node and cluster_resource_group are the class names for UCMDB 9.0 and 10.x.
    keystore - The path to the KeyStore file. This file should contain a certificate the client is capable of authenticating with on the uCMDB server.
    keystorePassword - The password associated with the keystore file.

Results\:
returnIpCIResult - The ID of the CI in UCMDB with an ip_address that is equal to the IP of the input hostname. 
returnHostCITypeResult - The CI type of the host that the returnIpCIResult is related. 
returnHostCIResult - The ID of the host CI in UCMDB that the returnIpCIResult is related. 

Responses\:
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully. 
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
4e696fc9-4ff9-4ca9-b80c-a729909136b8.27c6b8d5-131d-45c6-b80c-973b2a403001.prompt=Enter UCMDB Host Name\: 4e696fc9-4ff9-4ca9-b80c-a729909136b8.2adc7633-4ef3-4067-873b-1a9381c7aed7.prompt=Service Manager Version\: 4e696fc9-4ff9-4ca9-b80c-a729909136b8.3e6166c3-d42b-4703-924a-e478443f38e7.description=
This flow sends, stores or displays a notification message according to your notification type selection. You can use this flow to select how to be notified about the outcome of other flows. 

Inputs\:
    notifyData -  The content of the notification message.
    notifyMethod - The notification type. This value is not case sensitive.
Valid values\: Write to File, Email, Display or None
    subject - A summary of the notification content. 
    destination - The destination of the notification. You must specify a value for this input if "notifyMethod" is set to ‘Email’ or ‘Write to File’.
Valid values\: An email address or a file name
    notificationServer - The email server used to send the notification email message. If "notifyMethod" is set to ‘Email’, you must specify a value for this input.
    from - The email address of the sender of the notification email message.  If "notifyMethod" is set to ‘Email’, you must specify a value for this input.
    serverPort - The notification service’s server port. This field’s value is used when the "notifyMethod" is ‘Email’, but it is optional.
Default value\: 25
    htmlEmail - The value should be true if the email is in rich text/HTML format. The value should be false to send the email in plain text format.
Default value\: true

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Note\:
    To schedule a flow that uses this flow, you need to supply all the required fields for the used notification method. For example, if "notifyMethod" is set to ‘File’, the "destination" input must also be specified.

Examples\:
    This is a valid input example for storing a notification message to a file\:
      notifyData\: notificationContent
      notifyMethod\: Write to File
      subject\: notificationSubject
      destination\: C\:\Program File\notification.txt
4e696fc9-4ff9-4ca9-b80c-a729909136b8.40de5aa4-2c78-4416-a5c9-b0b122854fff.callout=CMDB collection and updates if required. 4e696fc9-4ff9-4ca9-b80c-a729909136b8.41e42315-7455-4540-bbf9-76c622fbb349.prompt=Notification option\: 4e696fc9-4ff9-4ca9-b80c-a729909136b8.4223e047-9366-434d-861b-8360c7bd164a.prompt=Protocol\: 4e696fc9-4ff9-4ca9-b80c-a729909136b8.44210a9b-bf04-4e20-be9f-dbfcf204e942.callout=Synchronize data from Service Manager with Partner ticketing system (JDBC, ODBC) 4e696fc9-4ff9-4ca9-b80c-a729909136b8.4a7f674f-815a-4568-8ab6-d680a94cd853.prompt=Please Enter a Host Name for Checking Its IP\: 4e696fc9-4ff9-4ca9-b80c-a729909136b8.4d8d8e11-b58e-4450-8615-7c596c43d410.prompt=Protocol\: 4e696fc9-4ff9-4ca9-b80c-a729909136b8.4d9b65b6-8de9-4abc-b965-27e3748e66d4.description=
Changes one or more attributes on an object.

Inputs\:
    cmdbHost - The host running UCMDB.
    cmdbPort - The UCMDB server port.
    protocol - The protocol used to connect to the UCMDB server. HTTPS (TLS) is supported only by UCMDB version 9.x and 10.x.
    Valid values\: http, https
    Default value\: http
    username - The user name used for the UCMDB server connection.
    password - The password associated with the  input value.
    objectId - The identifier of the object to modify.
    objectType - The type of the object to modify.
prop - A property to set (name\=value), The type of the property will be automatically determined. Additional properties can be added by making extra prop inputs with a number appended, such as prop1.
    cmdbVersion - The major version number of the UCMDB server.
Default value\: 7
Examples\: 7 (for UCMDB 7.0), 8 (for UCMDB 8.0)
    keystore - The path to the KeyStore file. This file should contain a certificate the client is capable of authenticating with on the uCMDB server.
    keystorePassword - The password associated with the keystore file.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Notes\:
    Due to the issue of UCMDB API, when integrate with UCMDB 9.0 or lower version,  if update the value of an attribute which is not editable, the API will come back with sucessful status, however the attribute won't get updated with the new value.
4e696fc9-4ff9-4ca9-b80c-a729909136b8.56bb1cdc-14da-4742-adf4-45cc53c01eb6.description=
Adds a new relationship to the CMDB.

Inputs\:
    cmdbHost - The host running UCMDB.
    cmdbPort - The UCMDB server port.
    protocol - The protocol used to connect to the UCMDB server. HTTPS (TLS) is supported only by UCMDB versions 9.x and 10.x.
Valid values\: http, https
Default value\: http
    username - The user name used for the UCMDB server connection.
    password - The password associated with the  input value.
    fromId - The identifier of the object from which the relationship is.
    fromType - The type of the object from which the relationship is. The  input is not used in the UCMDB API call for the integration with UCMDB 8.0 and above.
    toType - The type of the object to which the relationship is. The  input is not used in the UCMDB API call for the integration with UCMDB 8.0 and above.
    toId - The identifier of the object to which the relationship is.
    relationType - The type of the added relation.
Example\: containment
    prop - A property to add (name\=value). The type of the property is determined automatically. You can add properties by creating  inputs with an appended number (for example, ).
    cmdbVersion - The major version number of the UCMDB server.
Default value\: 7
Examples\: 7 (for UCMDB 7.0), 8 (for UCMDB 8.0)    
    keystore - The path to the KeyStore file. This file should contain a certificate the client is capable of authenticating with on the uCMDB server.
    keystorePassword - The password associated with the keystore file.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. The ID of the created relation.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

If this input is left empty, the short description of the created Incident will be empty. incidentNumber - The number of the Incident to be created. Example\: INC0100001 incidentCaller - The system ID of the Caller. Example\: 60792105db65120058d5788dbf961978 incidentLocation - The system ID of the Location. Example\: Software, Inquiry / Help incidentSubcategory - The Subcategory name in the form of a string. Example\: Email, Operating System incidentImpact - The Impact of the Incident, in the form of a positive integer between 1 and 3. Valid values\: 1, 2, 3 incidentUrgency - The Urgency of the Incident, in the form of a positive integer between 1 and 3. Valid values\: 1, 2, 3 incidentPriority - The Priority of the Incident, in the form of a positive integer between 1 and 5. Valid values\: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 incidentOpenedBy - The system ID of the entity that submitted the Incident. Example\: Phone, Email incidentState - The State of the Incident, in the form of a positive integer between 1 and 7. Each integer represents an Incident State as follows\: 1\=New, 2\=Active, 3\=Awaiting Problem, 4\=Awaiting User Info, 5\=Awaiting Evidence, 6\=Resolved, 7\=Closed. Valid values\: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7 incidentAssignmentGroup - The system ID of the Assignment Group. Example\: 60792105db65120058d5788dbf961978 incidentAssignedTo - The system ID of the entity to which the Incident should be assigned to. If responseCharacterSet is empty, the charset from the 'Content-Type' HTTP response header will be used. If responseCharacterSet is empty and the charset from the HTTP response Content-Type header is empty, the default value will be used. You should not use this for method\=HEAD or OPTIONS. Default value\: ISO-8859-1 followRedirects - Specifies whether the HTTP client automatically follows redirects. Redirects explicitly prohibited by the HTTP specification as requiring user intervention will not be followed (redirects on POST and PUT requests that are converted to GET requests). If you specify a non-boolean value, the default value is used. Default value\: true Valid values\: true, false requestCharacterSet - The character encoding to be used for the HTTP request body. If contentType is empty, the requestCharacterSet will use the default value. If contentType will include charset (ex.\: "application/json; charset\=UTF-8"), the requestCharacterSet value will overwrite the charset value from contentType input. This operation iterates through a list of values. It is not recommended to modify the value of the "list" and "separator" inputs during the iteration process.

Inputs\:
    list - The list to iterate through.
    separator - A delimiter separating the list elements.
Default value\: ‘,’ (comma) 

Results\:
    resultString - The current list element (if the response is "has more").

Responses\:
    has more - Another value was found in the list and it has been returned.
    no more - The iterator has gone through the entire list. This response is returned once per list iteration.  A subsequent call to the List iterator operation restarts the list iteration process.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Note\:
   The position of the iterator in the list is tracked by each step's unique identifier. Therefore, you can simultaneously iterate through the same list from multiple steps.

Retrieves an incident ticket's details

Inputs\:
host - The DNS name or IP Address of your Service Manager host.
port - The port to connect to your Service Manager host.
protocol - The protocol to connect to your Service Manager host. This value can be either HTTP or HTTPS.
username - The user name of the Service Manager host.
password - The password of the Service Manager user.
smVersion - The version of Service Manager. If the value is empty or contains spaces only, the default version 'sm93x' will be used.
id - ID of the ticket

Responses\:
success - The operation completed successfully.
failure - Error occurred.

Returns\:
smMessage - A brief message of a Service Manager request.
smMessages - Additional messages of a Service manager request.
smReturnCode - The return code of a Service Manager request.
smStatus - The return status of a Service Manager request.
alertStatus - Alert status.
assignee - Assignee's name.
assignmentGroup - Primary assignment group.
briefDescription - Brief description (single line).
category - Ticket category.
closedBy - Name of the agent who closed the ticket.
closedTime - Time of ticket closure.
closureCode - Closure code.
configItem - Configuration item.
contact - Contact name.
description - Ticket description (long).
id - Ticket ID.
journalUpdates - Update history (new-line delimited).
openedBy - Ticket opener.
openTime - Time ticket was last opened.
problemType - Problem type.
productType - Product type / sub-area.
resolution - Ticket resolution information.
resolutionFixType - Fix method for the ticket (Permanent or Temporary).
service - Affected service with ticket.
severity - Severity (sometimes called User Priority).
siteCategory - Site category.
slaAgreementID - SLA Agreement ID.
solution - Ticket solution.
subCategory - Subcategory / area.
ticketOwner - Ticket owner.
updatedBy - Username of last updater.
updatedTime - Time ticket last updated.

The fields below will be shown with a value only when getting an incident in SM 9.3x with Process Designer Content Pack 9.30.3 installed\:
status - Current Status.
phase - Current Phase.
escalated - Escalated.
majorIncident - Major Incident.
escalationTeam - Escalation Teams.
owner - Owner.
expectedResolutionTime - Expected Resolution Time.
